\title{symbayes: Threshold-Free, Mixture-Aware Symbiodiniaceae ITS2 Profiling}
\description{
\code{symbayes} provides a probabilistic alternative to SymPortal's deterministic
ITS2 type profiles. It reads SymPortal output and fits three complementary
mixture models, each answering a different question:
}
\details{
\describe{
\item{\strong{DMM} (\link{fit_dmm})}{How many discrete community \emph{types} does the
dataset support? Dirichlet-Multinomial Mixture with formal model
selection (Laplace/BIC). Hard assignment: each sample maps to one
component.}
\item{\strong{LDA} (\link{fit_lda})}{What is each sample \emph{made of}? Latent Dirichlet
Allocation with redundancy-based topic-number selection. Fractional
membership: a sample can be a mixture of topics.}
\item{\strong{HDP} (\link{fit_hdp})}{Threshold-free and mixture-aware: the number of
community types is inferred from the data via a Hierarchical Dirichlet
Process, and samples may be admixed.}
}
}
\section{The \code{sp} object and the membership schema}{
Every function takes and returns a single list of class \code{symbayes} (created
by \link{import}). Fitting a model writes a standardised \emph{membership} object into
\code{sp$dmm}, \code{sp$lda}, or \code{sp$hdp}, each with the same schema:

\describe{
\item{\code{theta}}{samples x groups membership matrix (near one-hot for DMM,
fractional for LDA/HDP)}
\item{\code{beta}}{groups x sequences exemplar compositions}
\item{\code{dominant}}{per-sample dominant group (factor)}
\item{\code{k}}{number of groups}
\item{\code{meta}}{model-specific extras (certainty, entropy, residual, ...)}
}

Because all three models expose the same schema, the \emph{generalist} plotting
functions (\link{plot_pcoa}, \link{plot_barplot}, \link{plot_exemplars},
\link{plot_contingency}, \link{plot_membership}) work on any fitted model via a
\code{model = c("dmm", "lda", "hdp")} argument.
